A total of 23 significantly over-represented canonical pathways were identified as differentially expressed between GIN-free Texel and Suffolk sheep (Table 4). The four most significant pathways all relate to processes of anti-viral /anti-bacterial innate immunity and were all more highly expressed in the Suffolk lambs relative to the Texel lambs. The four pathways and the DE genes assigned to each pathway are as follows:
Role of Pattern Recognition Receptors in Recognition of Bacteria and Viruses: RIG-I, MDA-5, DECTIN-2, IRF3, OAS1, OAS2, C1QC, C1QB, EIF2AK2, RNASEL, C3AR1 (Fig 2);
Activation of IRF by Cytosolic Pattern Recognition Receptors: RIG-I, MDA-5, DAI, ISG-54, TBK1, IRF3, IRF9, STAT2, ADAR1, ISG15 (Fig 3);
Role of RIG-I-like Receptors in Antiviral Innate Immunity: RIG-I, MDA-5, TBK1, IRF3, TRIM2, (Fig 4);
Interferon Signaling: IFIT1, IFIT3, IRF9, OAS1, MX1, STAT, (Fig 5).
